	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#D6D1BE">	
		
	
			</font>
			<font face="Verdana" size="1"><b>
			<font color="black">--Submited by:&nbsp;
			<a href="mailto:mariko28@juno.com">Cleome</a></font> 
			<font color="black">On:&nbsp;03/31/1999 10:43:06 AM&nbsp;&nbsp;
			(<font color="blue"><B>List by:</font> <a href="http://www.everlore.com/races_classes/classes.asp?CID=1&mode=details&type=races&pg=1&sortby=1">Front</a><font color="black">/</font><a href="http://www.everlore.com/races_classes/classes.asp?CID=1&mode=details&type=races&pg=1&sortby=2">Back</a></B></a>)
			
			</font></b></font>
	
		</td>
		
	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Human and Half-Elf Druids start out at Surefall Glade, which is a bit NE of the city Qeynos.  The Glade is a quiet little place--there's no bank  and you'll have to journey to Qeynos for any vocational kits and armor beyond a shield.  There's a Druid guild and a Ranger guild.  You can buy your spells for the first few levels there, provision and occasionally find a starting weapon.  The caves behind the falls have bears which are friendly to Druids &amp; Rangers--stop by and feed them a fish or two.  The caves also have a few poachers who are definitely unfriendly, so don't drop your guard back there (i.e. go fishing, meditate, memorize spells) until you're higher level.  The exit to Qeynos Hills is through a long tunnel, so nightvision or a light source is good.  The hunting for new characters is rats, bats, snakes, decaying skeletons and gnoll pups in the Hills.  There are guards at the entrance, so you do have a safe place to retreat to.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#D6D1BE">	
		
	
			</font>
			<font face="Verdana" size="1"><b>
			<font color="black">--Submited by:&nbsp;
			<a href="mailto:apetyo@ecst.csuchico.edu">Balthamel</a></font> 
			<font color="black">On:&nbsp;04/18/1999 10:52:23 AM&nbsp;&nbsp;
			</font></b></font>
	
		</td>
		
	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				The starting point for the Wood Elf Druid lies in the City of Kelethin.<BR>
Kelethin at first is a little bit confusing at first but after wandering around a bit<BR>
it becomes much more familar.  Greater Faydark is a great area to hunt because of the large<BR>
diversity of monsters there.  At levels 1-4 you'll most likely stay at the ruins near kelethin<BR>
killing decaying skeletons, bats, wasp drones, widow hatchlings, and orc pawns.  This forest is<BR>
home to the black wolf friend of Tunare and the Druidic order.  Kelethin contains a variety of<BR>
different shops to purchase armor and traveling gear such as backpacks and bags.  Weapons can be<BR>
found on most monsters in the forest so save your money for spells.  Spells are available in the Druid<BR>
and ranger guild within Kelethin, and those that cannot be found there can be found in the wizards guild<BR>
in Felwithe.  Once a Druid ascends to the 5th level and above his options for hunting open up a bit.  The <BR>
great thing about the greater faydark area is that there are many places to fight.  There are the bandit camps<BR>
the Orc camps, Crushbone area, and you can even venture to the ButcherBlock mountains for a bit of a change.<BR>
  
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#D6D1BE">	
		
	
